# API and Data Fetching Guidelines

## API Routes

- Use Next.js Route Handlers for API endpoints
- Organize API routes by domain or feature
- Implement proper error handling and status codes
- Validate request data with zod or similar
- Implement rate limiting for public endpoints
- Use appropriate HTTP methods (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE)

## Data Fetching

- Prefer server components for data fetching
- Implement proper caching strategies
- Use SWR or React Query for client-side data fetching
- Handle loading, error, and empty states
- Implement optimistic updates when appropriate
- Use proper TypeScript types for API responses

## Authentication and Authorization

- Validate authentication in API routes
- Implement proper authorization checks
- Use middleware for common auth logic
- Handle expired tokens and refresh flows
- Implement proper CSRF protection

## Error Handling

- Use consistent error response format
- Implement proper logging for server errors
- Return appropriate HTTP status codes
- Provide user-friendly error messages
- Handle network errors gracefully

## Performance

- Implement proper caching headers
- Use edge functions for low-latency APIs
- Optimize database queries
- Implement pagination for large datasets
- Use appropriate fetch cache options

## Security

- Validate and sanitize all user inputs
- Implement proper CORS settings
- Use HTTPS for all API calls
- Protect against common vulnerabilities (XSS, CSRF, etc.)
- Implement proper rate limiting

## Testing

- Write unit tests for API handlers
- Implement integration tests for API flows
- Mock external dependencies
- Test error scenarios
- Test performance with load testing